WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:16.120
Well, happy Thursday, everybody. Welcome to the Data Science Hangout. If this is your

00:00:16.120 --> 00:00:20.760
first time joining us here today, it's so nice to meet you. Thanks for spending your

00:00:20.760 --> 00:00:26.760
Thursday with us. Actually calling in from the POSIT office. Nobody's here with me today,

00:00:26.760 --> 00:00:33.599
but I have this nice view of the water. But if we haven't met yet, I'm Rachel Dempsey.

00:00:33.599 --> 00:00:39.720
I host the Data Science Hangout and lead customer marketing at POSIT. This is our open space

00:00:39.720 --> 00:00:45.279
to chat about data science leadership, questions you're facing and getting to hear about what's

00:00:45.279 --> 00:00:50.480
going on in the world of data across many different industries. And so we're here the

00:00:50.480 --> 00:00:56.560
same space, same time every Thursday. So if you're watching this recording on YouTube

00:00:56.560 --> 00:01:02.759
later, you can add it to your calendar with the details below. But together, we're all

00:01:02.759 --> 00:01:08.360
dedicated to making this a welcoming community for everybody. And so we love hearing from

00:01:08.360 --> 00:01:15.680
everyone no matter your years of experience, titles, industry or even languages that you

00:01:15.680 --> 00:01:21.720
work in. So every week I'm joined by a different leader here from our community who joins us

00:01:21.720 --> 00:01:28.279
to share their experience and answer questions from you all. So to let you know how to ask

00:01:28.279 --> 00:01:33.559
questions, first of all, it's totally okay to just listen in if you want to. But there's

00:01:33.559 --> 00:01:39.720
also three ways you can jump in to ask questions. So you can raise your hand on Zoom, and I'll

00:01:39.720 --> 00:01:46.040
be here looking out. You can put questions in the Zoom chat. And feel free to just put

00:01:46.040 --> 00:01:51.000
a little star next to it if you want me to read it, or else I can call on you to ask

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:56.519
the question live. And then lastly, we have a Slido link, which Tyler will share here

00:01:56.519 --> 00:02:01.639
in right when I said that. Thanks, Tyler, where you can ask questions anonymously too.

00:02:01.639 --> 00:02:07.440
But with all that, thank you so much for joining us here today. And I'm so excited to be joined

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:14.800
by my co-host, Mike Lopez. Mike is Senior Director of Data and Analytics at the NFL

00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:19.800
National Football League. Mike, I'd love to have you introduce yourself, maybe tell us

00:02:19.800 --> 00:02:24.000
something you like to do outside of work too, and share a little bit about your role.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:28.960
Thanks, Rachel. And thanks to everyone at Posit for organizing these. It is an exciting

00:02:28.960 --> 00:02:36.320
time to be in football data. And we just have a lot of questions that we have to try and

00:02:36.320 --> 00:02:43.520
use sort of naive or advanced models for, because there is so much about the world of

00:02:43.520 --> 00:02:49.440
football that we are just starting to learn. My background was, I was a high school teacher,

00:02:49.440 --> 00:02:56.960
turned PhD student, turned assistant professor at college. And at that point, the influx

00:02:56.960 --> 00:03:01.759
of football data became apparent. The league started getting next gen stats, which is each

00:03:01.759 --> 00:03:06.160
player wears a pair of RFID chips in their shoulder pads. And you sort of went from an

00:03:06.160 --> 00:03:12.320
NFL data history where every game had 160 plays, so 160 rows of data, which everyone was sort of

00:03:12.320 --> 00:03:18.399
analyzing locally on their laptops, to now a world where we have this tracking data, both RFID based

00:03:18.399 --> 00:03:23.520
and then now even video based. And it's just hard. There's just a lot that we are learning and trying

00:03:23.520 --> 00:03:29.279
to figure out. So my job is to organize a group of really intelligent young data scientists that

00:03:29.279 --> 00:03:33.679
are helping us and helping the league make better decisions. Awesome. Thanks, Mike. And

00:03:33.679 --> 00:03:44.479
something you like to do outside of work too. Our preseason starts tonight. And I sort of

00:03:44.479 --> 00:03:50.399
now realize that from now until the end of March, most of my spare time is going to be keeping an

00:03:50.399 --> 00:03:57.360
eye on what happens in everything related to the NFL. So my spare time was over the summer. I

00:03:57.360 --> 00:04:01.360
have three young kids, and so hanging out with them is really how I spend my spare time.

00:04:02.240 --> 00:04:07.199
But tonight, that is now done with an eye on the NFL game that's on the television. So watching

00:04:07.199 --> 00:04:14.880
football is what you do in your spare time. Yeah. It's a nice side gig. That's great. Well,

00:04:15.759 --> 00:04:19.440
Mike, I know there'll be a lot of questions coming in from everybody shortly here.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:26.959
But just hearing that initially about how you're using data from the RFID tags on the players, I

00:04:26.959 --> 00:04:33.440
love to just understand a little bit more about what that process looks like and how you ingest

00:04:33.440 --> 00:04:38.399
that data, what you do with that data. Just kind of walking me through a little bit of that process.

00:04:38.399 --> 00:04:43.920
So the league has, I would say, two data warehouses of sort of systems of storing

00:04:43.920 --> 00:04:49.200
data. In the early 2000s, that's when the league initially started building a lot of the SQL

00:04:49.200 --> 00:04:53.920
server that the clubs still use and that we would still use. That would be your traditional game

00:04:53.920 --> 00:05:00.079
stats. So if you play fantasy football, the yards caught by wide receiver or the quarterbacks

00:05:02.559 --> 00:05:06.720
yards per game or whatever that would be, that would be your traditional game stats.

00:05:07.600 --> 00:05:13.920
In 2015 was when the league first, it might've been 14 or 15, I wasn't with the league at that

00:05:13.920 --> 00:05:18.799
point, but that's when the league started collecting the player tracking data and they

00:05:18.799 --> 00:05:23.279
had seen it catch on other sports and it was driven by the media group out in Los Angeles.

00:05:23.279 --> 00:05:28.880
And so if the base game stats are stored in New York, the media data is stored and managed by

00:05:28.880 --> 00:05:33.839
Zebra and the next gen stats team out in LA. We ingest it. There are a couple of ways that

00:05:33.839 --> 00:05:40.320
the league gets it. One is using an API. The second is there is a SQL server that now is

00:05:40.320 --> 00:05:47.279
dedicated to organizing and managing that data. One of the unique things about the tracking data

00:05:47.279 --> 00:05:51.839
is that it really sort of changes your data pipeline and how you organize and manage your code

00:05:52.480 --> 00:05:58.320
because you used to be able to just sort of load every NFL game, play-by-play, whatever it has,

00:05:59.119 --> 00:06:05.839
and analyze it, right? Fit a model, make a graph. Now you have to be a little bit more articulate

00:06:05.839 --> 00:06:08.640
about how you're doing that. I don't know if articulate is the right word, but you have to

00:06:08.640 --> 00:06:13.359
be a little bit, you sort of be forward thinking. A lot of times what we do is just sort of fit it

00:06:13.359 --> 00:06:18.399
on a play, right? If you want to figure out was the wide receiver open, don't try to do that on

00:06:18.399 --> 00:06:24.000
every play that wide receiver has ever done. Just try to do it on one play and identify a way of

00:06:25.119 --> 00:06:30.880
whatever metric you're creating or looking at openness for that wide receiver and doing it

00:06:30.880 --> 00:06:35.760
on that play. That takes a lot of time because you're probably the first person to think about

00:06:35.760 --> 00:06:40.640
your level of ranking that openness or whatever. We're doing a lot of things in the league to

00:06:40.640 --> 00:06:44.720
increase the awareness of football data and to give people the code so that they can build

00:06:45.679 --> 00:06:50.079
their new work off of it, but it's still new. And then once you've done it on that one play,

00:06:50.079 --> 00:06:53.760
then try to do it again, right? Try to write a function to do it on the game.

00:06:54.640 --> 00:06:59.279
And then obviously extract it to all players and all games and all that stuff takes time. So

00:06:59.279 --> 00:07:06.799
that's kind of how the traditional, you would be an analyst in the year 2012 or 13 and you'd

00:07:06.799 --> 00:07:11.839
download CSVs and you'd analyze all the plays at once. Now you have to be a little bit more

00:07:11.839 --> 00:07:15.119
cognizant about how to do that just because of the size of the tracking data.

00:07:15.119 --> 00:07:18.880
Thank you. It's really helpful. I see a ton of questions starting to come in here.

00:07:18.880 --> 00:07:23.679
Devin, I see you asked one in the chat. Do you want to jump in? And I can ask the question if

00:07:23.679 --> 00:07:29.119
you want to jump in with more context, feel free. But the question was, what kind of decision-making

00:07:29.119 --> 00:07:36.079
is your work driving at the league level versus the Moneyball team versus team decision-making?

00:07:36.079 --> 00:07:39.839
And Devin said, thanks for powering my fantasy leagues as well.

00:07:39.839 --> 00:07:45.600
So we are primarily interested in what happens on the field. And if it happens in the field,

00:07:45.600 --> 00:07:50.480
we're hoping to measure it. And in the sense that that's how close are our games? How exciting are

00:07:50.480 --> 00:07:55.519
they? What are the trends and how teams are calling plays and how players are playing and

00:07:55.519 --> 00:08:00.799
how coaches are coaching? We do a lot with our officiating group trying to help them make better

00:08:00.799 --> 00:08:05.679
decisions. And then also both the sort of on-field decisions, but also the training.

00:08:06.640 --> 00:08:11.359
We work with player health and safety on making sure that the rules of the game are sort of the

00:08:11.359 --> 00:08:19.519
best match between keeping the player safe, making sure that their equipment is as sort of top-notch

00:08:19.519 --> 00:08:25.839
as it can be. And then also going back to the rules, like whatever we talk about a rule of

00:08:25.839 --> 00:08:30.720
the game, it's driven by, does it make the game more competitive? Does it make the game safer?

00:08:31.359 --> 00:08:35.119
Can our officials officiate it? Does it keep the game exciting? Things like that.

00:08:35.119 --> 00:08:41.440
So we try to organize a lot of our sort of support for the league around a lot of those questions.

00:08:42.799 --> 00:08:47.119
The teams make the decisions to go forward on fourth down. They make the decisions to

00:08:47.119 --> 00:08:53.679
challenge a play, to start a quarterback or to draft a certain player. But a lot of what we're

00:08:53.679 --> 00:08:57.840
trying to help with is that there are new tools to help with those decisions. There's new metrics

00:08:57.840 --> 00:09:02.719
that we can help create. There's new data sets that we can provide them. And ultimately what

00:09:02.719 --> 00:09:07.760
they do with that is obviously up to them. I know you just touched upon the health data,

00:09:07.760 --> 00:09:12.719
but Geraldine, I saw you had a question about that. Do you want to ask a follow-up there?

00:09:12.719 --> 00:09:16.080
Yeah, because when I asked that question, you were mostly talking about tactics and plays,

00:09:16.080 --> 00:09:22.960
et cetera. So I was wondering, do you guys also analyze players' health stats around things like

00:09:24.159 --> 00:09:29.840
whether or not they get concussions from impacts or dehydration, or is there like a separate team

00:09:29.840 --> 00:09:32.880
that deals with that? So as part of the NFL collective bargaining

00:09:32.880 --> 00:09:37.679
agreement with the Players Association, the league doesn't analyze that data themselves,

00:09:37.679 --> 00:09:44.080
but there are two third parties that do, two companies that we work with a lot, IQVIA and

00:09:44.080 --> 00:09:48.960
BioCorps are their names. And they're both really good from an epidemiological side and an

00:09:48.960 --> 00:09:56.640
engineering side at looking at what are the trends in injuries? What are the both rates of concussions

00:09:56.640 --> 00:10:01.280
or injuries or missed time injuries or leg strains? How have those changed over time as

00:10:01.280 --> 00:10:07.359
athletes have gotten faster and the teams are passing more and things like that. So those are

00:10:07.359 --> 00:10:13.280
collaborations that we're a part of. The specific raw injury data is not something we touch on a lot

00:10:13.280 --> 00:10:19.200
only in the sense that when it comes time for changing the punt play or the kickoff play or

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:24.479
the rules around how to protect the quarterback, it's never just a health and safety question.

00:10:24.479 --> 00:10:31.359
It's a health and safety and an officiating question and a sort of competitive question

00:10:31.359 --> 00:10:36.559
about if this is going to make our games closer or more blowouts or less exciting or less tradition,

00:10:36.559 --> 00:10:44.239
things like that. So a lot of the way that we try to work with those types of questions is how does

00:10:44.239 --> 00:10:50.559
this impact the entirety of the game? And the other aspect that I think is really neat about

00:10:50.559 --> 00:10:56.400
where football is now is that it's not just the game data, it's also the practice data. And so

00:10:58.400 --> 00:11:06.239
most clubs have performance scientists that work with trainers on managing player load and sort of

00:11:06.239 --> 00:11:12.159
optimizing player performance from a, I think both a performance and an injury side. And that's not

00:11:12.159 --> 00:11:17.359
stuff that we're allowed to help with, but we do know that a lot of clubs are going down that route.

00:11:17.359 --> 00:11:20.320
Greg, I see you had a question in the chat too. Do you want to jump in here?

00:11:22.559 --> 00:11:27.280
Yeah, sure. Thanks Michael for being here today. I actually got a chance to see you speak at the

00:11:27.280 --> 00:11:31.119
University of Denver back before the pandemic, which seems like a lifetime ago at the sports

00:11:31.119 --> 00:11:36.239
analytics conference. So I was just wondering if you have any thoughts on how transferable

00:11:38.080 --> 00:11:43.840
analytics skills, sports analytics specifically are across leagues, right? If you build up

00:11:43.919 --> 00:11:49.679
experience with baseball or basketball, how does that transfer to football or other sports? I know

00:11:49.679 --> 00:11:54.400
some of them are more emerging than others. Yeah. I mean, I honestly, I don't think you can be a

00:11:54.400 --> 00:11:58.400
great sports data scientist without really having a sense of what's going on in other sports.

00:11:59.280 --> 00:12:05.200
So I would say it's really twofold. One is the skills themselves are transferable. If you can

00:12:05.200 --> 00:12:09.359
code tracking data in football, you can code it in baseball, you can code it in basketball, etc.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:15.599
It might take you a little bit of time to get up to speed, but the specific functions that you're

00:12:15.599 --> 00:12:21.440
writing or the specific ways that you're transforming the tracking data into metrics

00:12:21.440 --> 00:12:26.239
that you can communicate with a coach, that you can do in any sport, right? Once you can do it in

00:12:26.239 --> 00:12:33.119
one. The hard part is being able to do it in one. So I think that's one area. And then the second

00:12:33.119 --> 00:12:38.320
one, which is really maybe just as important is what are the other sports doing? What are they

00:12:38.320 --> 00:12:45.520
looking at? One recent thing that's caught on to a lot of folks in football is that baseball teams

00:12:45.520 --> 00:12:50.960
no longer draft a player and then send the player out there and the player performs or doesn't

00:12:50.960 --> 00:12:57.760
perform. They're now doing things in training to maximize the player's launch angle or their exit

00:12:57.760 --> 00:13:04.719
velocity or their swing path because they think that they can take a player and help them improve

00:13:05.359 --> 00:13:12.559
using data. And I don't think football has always been that way. I think maybe the corollary

00:13:12.559 --> 00:13:16.640
would be you would have a quarterback and you throw the quarterback out there and they'd either

00:13:16.640 --> 00:13:21.039
complete the pass or miss it and maybe you could get a new offensive coordinator. But maybe now

00:13:21.039 --> 00:13:25.119
you could be thinking about where is the quarterback holding the ball? What is their

00:13:25.119 --> 00:13:30.799
path to throw it? Is there something that we can do that's sort of maybe the corollary of a

00:13:30.799 --> 00:13:36.080
swing in baseball? So that's one example that isn't certainly the only example, but I think

00:13:36.080 --> 00:13:41.440
it's sort of a combination of both the hard skills, hands-on keyboard stuff that if you can code, you

00:13:41.440 --> 00:13:45.840
can code. And if you know sports, I think that's going to certainly transfer.

00:13:45.840 --> 00:13:50.080
But there's also an awareness of what are other leagues doing? What are the metrics that they've

00:13:50.080 --> 00:13:56.159
come up with? I think it certainly helps in the data science to have that background

00:13:56.159 --> 00:14:00.559
and that skill set because there's just so much out there that the NFL can learn from other sports.

00:14:00.799 --> 00:14:05.359
And I do think specifically given some of the competitions and the work that the football

00:14:05.359 --> 00:14:08.960
has done in the last couple years, other sports are now learning stuff from football too.

00:14:08.960 --> 00:14:14.719
Great, I appreciate that. Thank you very much. Mike, we talk a lot about community in the Data Science

00:14:14.719 --> 00:14:20.080
Hangout and I think the Big Data Bowl is an amazing community initiative that stands out to

00:14:20.080 --> 00:14:27.280
me. And I was wondering, do you see this initiative happening in other sports or other industries now?

00:14:27.280 --> 00:14:31.599
And do you have any tips for people who are trying to do something similar?

00:14:32.960 --> 00:14:36.320
And it might be helpful to just explain what the Big Data Bowl is too.

00:14:36.320 --> 00:14:44.799
So one of my weaknesses is I hold grudges. And so I used to always get a little bit irritated

00:14:44.799 --> 00:14:53.440
with some well-known sports conferences and organizations that would maybe run hackathons

00:14:53.440 --> 00:14:58.880
or share data in ways that, as an academic and as somebody who supports reproducible research,

00:14:58.880 --> 00:15:04.640
maybe didn't have those same values. And so when I started at the league, I was pretty steadfast

00:15:04.640 --> 00:15:10.400
that I thought the league could do a better job of sharing data. And one of the ways that we've

00:15:10.400 --> 00:15:16.479
done that is through an event called the Big Data Bowl. And it has a couple purposes. One is let's

00:15:16.479 --> 00:15:22.880
innovate in football. And we can be talented all we want as a league office and whatnot,

00:15:22.880 --> 00:15:27.679
but there's only so much that our group can do and the Next Gen Stats group can do. There's just

00:15:27.679 --> 00:15:33.280
a lot of other things. And the idea being that there's just a lot we can do. And if you share

00:15:33.280 --> 00:15:38.400
data, people will analyze it. So the quote from Field of Dreams is, if you build it, they will

00:15:38.400 --> 00:15:45.679
come. If you share the data, they will analyze it, especially in sports data. So that's one of the

00:15:45.679 --> 00:15:51.679
main reasons we did it. We also have the motivation where we have this complex data set that no one's

00:15:51.679 --> 00:15:57.760
ever looked at. At least this was our initial philosophy in 2018. And if that's how we feel,

00:15:57.760 --> 00:16:03.599
that's also how the 32 NFL teams feel. And when you work at a league office, you're in some ways

00:16:04.400 --> 00:16:09.520
employed by the 32 teams. And so we're doing it for them. We're doing it to give them a pipeline

00:16:09.520 --> 00:16:15.119
of analytic staffers that they can hire to go answer their own questions. And one of the really

00:16:15.119 --> 00:16:20.320
neat things is, and I've sort of hinted at this, is that this is an opportunity for anyone to come

00:16:20.320 --> 00:16:27.359
in and analyze. And it really levels the playing field in the sense that before, when you would

00:16:27.359 --> 00:16:35.119
hire in sports data, you might look at GPA, or you might look at where the person went to college,

00:16:35.119 --> 00:16:42.719
or you might look at maybe where they interned last summer. Now you're looking at their code,

00:16:42.719 --> 00:16:47.760
right? You're looking at what they built. You're looking at what is their level of thoughtfulness

00:16:47.760 --> 00:16:52.000
in the questions and the way they communicate their results, which ultimately that's how you're

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:56.799
evaluated when you're on a team, right? If you're on a data science team and that your job is to

00:16:56.799 --> 00:17:02.479
build interpretable metrics and to communicate those and to do a good job of validating your

00:17:02.479 --> 00:17:07.920
models and things like that, that's what the big data role is all about. So we've seen a lot of,

00:17:07.920 --> 00:17:12.560
one of the neat things is that now people are copying football and that was never a place where

00:17:12.560 --> 00:17:18.160
football was before. There was the big data derby and horse racing. There was the big data cup,

00:17:19.520 --> 00:17:25.680
which staff leads put on in hockey. I think there was like now a fantasy football one.

00:17:26.959 --> 00:17:33.920
And it's pretty humbling to know that largely started with the NFL sharing data and being

00:17:33.920 --> 00:17:40.400
open about it. So we're certainly open to more leagues doing it. In terms of advice,

00:17:42.959 --> 00:17:49.280
the number one thing that we found is that the crowdsourced metrics are always better than

00:17:49.280 --> 00:17:58.479
anything we've ever come up with ourselves. And the more thoughtful and sort of, I guess,

00:18:00.400 --> 00:18:05.280
sort of thinking forward about what people will analyze, I think companies will get the most out

00:18:05.280 --> 00:18:10.319
of it. Like we've had competitions that have immediately turned into metrics that are shared

00:18:10.319 --> 00:18:20.319
on air. And our 2020 competition was on rushing yards. And within maybe 11 months from the contest

00:18:20.319 --> 00:18:28.560
ending, you watch the NFC title game, which has maybe 30 million viewers. They're watching a

00:18:28.560 --> 00:18:37.119
metric that came from our competition. And that's sort of a really exciting aspect of that competition.

00:18:37.119 --> 00:18:42.719
And so the better questions you ask, the better answers you'll get. But I think overall,

00:18:42.719 --> 00:18:46.319
we've certainly found that the crowdsourced approach has really helped.

00:18:46.880 --> 00:18:51.520
That's amazing. I was just sharing in the chat, last year's winners actually spoke at a

00:18:52.239 --> 00:18:55.920
Posit meetup. So if anybody wants to save that and check it out too.

00:18:57.920 --> 00:19:00.959
Yu, I see you've had your hand raised for a bit here. Do you want to jump in?

00:19:01.599 --> 00:19:07.359
Sure. Hi, Michael. Thank you for being here. I have one question. So what type of data are you

00:19:07.359 --> 00:19:14.640
using for the analysis? Are they tabular structure data or unstructured data like images or recording

00:19:14.640 --> 00:19:20.079
from the game directly? If the data are unstructured, how do you process them before

00:19:20.079 --> 00:19:26.400
you can use them for analysis and modeling? Yeah, good question. I would say with each

00:19:26.400 --> 00:19:30.719
passing year, we're getting to more unstructured data. But I think the league has done a pretty

00:19:30.719 --> 00:19:35.040
good job. And when you're at a league office, we have a large number of data engineers that help

00:19:35.599 --> 00:19:40.959
that ensure our SQL tables are clean and easy to read from. I would say most of it's pretty

00:19:40.959 --> 00:19:46.239
structured. And the other reality is with player tracking data, at least in the NFL,

00:19:47.280 --> 00:19:53.040
because it's RFID based, it's very accurate. And so it's a tabular format. In fact, if you go to

00:19:53.040 --> 00:19:57.599
our big datable site, you can download it as a CSV and it's a big data set, but it comes out clean.

00:19:58.239 --> 00:20:03.040
That's not necessarily the case with maybe some of the newer data sets we'd be getting into.

00:20:03.040 --> 00:20:08.239
If you talk about like video tracking, which would be like taking from an image and then trying to

00:20:08.239 --> 00:20:14.479
look at player location. One of the ways that football is going is that we have RFID tags

00:20:15.040 --> 00:20:21.119
on all 32 NFL teams and all the players and all the games. However, those players come from a pool

00:20:21.119 --> 00:20:27.040
of college players. The NFL can't make college players wear those same RFID tags. And so when

00:20:27.040 --> 00:20:31.359
you want college data, you either have your traditional stats or you've got to use video

00:20:31.359 --> 00:20:38.640
based data. And so a lot of that video based data on college players is stuff that is a little

00:20:38.640 --> 00:20:42.800
messier. And so that would be where you would have to extract it from imaging and things like that.

00:20:43.359 --> 00:20:49.280
There are companies out there that do that. And it's sort of, I don't know if it's an arms race,

00:20:49.280 --> 00:20:54.959
but I do know that NFL teams are really interested in those skills because of the way that before

00:20:54.959 --> 00:21:01.040
you would have to have a dozen scouts go out and watch videos of the teams in the northeast and the

00:21:01.040 --> 00:21:06.640
southeast and all over, you'd send scouts. And teams still do that. But now if you can get some

00:21:06.640 --> 00:21:13.119
of that insight by coming up with an algorithm that can take the data from the video and turn

00:21:13.119 --> 00:21:17.520
it into a nice usable format, that can certainly save you some time and maybe get you some insight

00:21:17.520 --> 00:21:23.040
you weren't getting otherwise. I see so many great questions coming in here. I'm just trying to

00:21:23.680 --> 00:21:29.599
sort through some of them. But Lisa, I see you had a question a bit earlier on Mike's transition

00:21:30.239 --> 00:21:37.680
from academia to the NFL. Do you want to jump in? Sure. Yeah. I'm Lisa. I was just curious about

00:21:38.239 --> 00:21:46.479
how you made the transition from academia to working for the NFL and how you think that

00:21:46.479 --> 00:21:52.079
academic experience was helpful. And then maybe again, this is probably selfish, but like how did

00:21:52.079 --> 00:22:00.319
you sort of market that academic skill set? I think the most helpful part about being in academia

00:22:00.319 --> 00:22:05.439
is that you are evaluated. And I was at a small liberal arts college. You're evaluated on your

00:22:05.439 --> 00:22:10.400
teaching. So you have to be a good teacher, right? I was a tenure track assistant professor

00:22:10.959 --> 00:22:14.959
and evals would come in. And when you weren't doing a good job communicating to your students,

00:22:15.680 --> 00:22:23.119
that's going to ding you or whatever. So I think that's the most helpful skill set is that my job

00:22:23.119 --> 00:22:29.920
was to take statistical methods and distill them down to students who were learning it.

00:22:32.160 --> 00:22:41.599
I've been teaching R for maybe some software for a decade. But when you do that in 2020 or whatever,

00:22:41.599 --> 00:22:45.920
I couldn't be teaching the same stuff I was teaching in 2010 because software was entirely

00:22:45.920 --> 00:22:51.280
different. So you also have to sort of keep up to date. And that's kind of a lot of what we do now.

00:22:51.280 --> 00:22:59.520
Like our job is to communicate statistical results or methods to folks that aren't statistics experts.

00:22:59.520 --> 00:23:06.959
Now, instead of students, now it's executives. And one of the things that we are constantly

00:23:06.959 --> 00:23:12.479
working on is what do we show? How much is too much? When do we lose them? How many plots is

00:23:12.479 --> 00:23:18.640
too many plots? Do they need to know the ins and outs of our models? And whereas when you're

00:23:18.640 --> 00:23:23.280
teaching, you really need to communicate all the ins and outs. Certainly, we don't do that now.

00:23:24.079 --> 00:23:28.400
But I think there's a lot of the experience that was most helpful was teaching and communicating

00:23:28.400 --> 00:23:35.040
results. We don't do as much writing. I don't have as many research papers maybe as I used to would

00:23:35.040 --> 00:23:41.439
have. But now, for better or for worse, I spend a lot of time making presentations. And I think a

00:23:41.439 --> 00:23:46.319
lot of that's the same approach where you're trying to take what you've learned and distill

00:23:46.319 --> 00:23:54.880
it into a template that others can understand. I started in 2018 when I worked at the league

00:23:54.880 --> 00:24:02.239
office, maybe doing one PowerPoint deck every couple months. And now, for better or for worse,

00:24:02.719 --> 00:24:07.119
I have to do that a lot because I have a really talented group of data scientists that are coming

00:24:07.119 --> 00:24:16.160
up with so many cool things. And I am now helping them curate material to share with executives.

00:24:16.160 --> 00:24:23.760
And there's, like I mentioned at the start, there's a lot that we can do. And trying to

00:24:23.760 --> 00:24:28.319
figure out how to communicate that goes back to that experience in academia where you're writing

00:24:28.319 --> 00:24:35.119
a journal article or you're writing a summary of your work. So that's where it's been most

00:24:35.119 --> 00:24:42.800
valuable. And I also think one of the cool aspects about where we are now is that there's just

00:24:42.800 --> 00:24:47.199
still a lot to learn. And that's no different than being in academia where you're an expert

00:24:47.199 --> 00:24:52.400
in something and you're trying to build the next tool or you're trying to build the next model or

00:24:52.400 --> 00:24:59.520
the next paper. And there's, you know, I think it's not that, you know, I like to often refer to

00:24:59.520 --> 00:25:04.160
our work as we just, we have a laundry list and sometimes our job is to just start at the top.

00:25:04.160 --> 00:25:07.520
What's the most important thing we can do? And that's not much different when you're in academia

00:25:07.520 --> 00:25:10.800
and trying to do the same thing. So great question. And I don't know if I answered it right, but

00:25:10.800 --> 00:25:16.959
that's where I would think. Yeah, that was great. I took some notes. So thanks. Of course. Thank you.

00:25:16.959 --> 00:25:20.880
Can we stay on this topic for just a bit here? When you were saying, when you were talking about

00:25:20.880 --> 00:25:26.640
the communication skills that have transferred over, I was curious if you do have certain tips

00:25:26.640 --> 00:25:32.959
for us for communicating to executives or what you've learned in many of those presentations

00:25:32.959 --> 00:25:37.119
you've given. Yeah. I mean, we've tried and failed a lot. I mean, there's things that I've pushed for

00:25:37.119 --> 00:25:42.079
or we felt strongly about that other people were like, yeah. And then there's other things where

00:25:42.079 --> 00:25:47.439
maybe I didn't feel as passionate about. And then suddenly maybe every, maybe the presentation got

00:25:47.439 --> 00:25:54.239
shared a lot more widely and I read about it the next day on ESPN.com. So I, it's hard to really

00:25:54.239 --> 00:25:59.599
know, like I haven't kept a spreadsheet of like what's worked or what hasn't in terms of communicating

00:25:59.599 --> 00:26:06.640
results. I think the, we have to have good data visualization. If we don't, we just, we can't do

00:26:06.640 --> 00:26:14.319
our job. And I think I spend probably, my team would probably complain about how I do this, but

00:26:14.319 --> 00:26:19.520
like, I probably complain about things that I, if this was a student paper that like, I probably

00:26:19.520 --> 00:26:25.040
wouldn't, right. Because I have to make sure that the work that is being presented is as clear

00:26:25.040 --> 00:26:30.000
and concise as it possibly can be. It can't be confusing. It has to have the right annotations.

00:26:30.800 --> 00:26:36.000
The stuff that has come out in ggplot in the last couple of years and also in GT with like the

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:40.560
sort of visualizing and tables has been really helpful in that front because for a while,

00:26:41.520 --> 00:26:46.160
like we would have to make tables in an old school format, right. Or I'd have to add annotations in

00:26:46.160 --> 00:26:51.599
PowerPoint because, you know, you couldn't code that. So that's, that's probably the most important

00:26:51.599 --> 00:26:58.479
thing is, is your, your viz has to be top notch. I also, and this just comes partly from experience,

00:26:58.479 --> 00:27:02.800
partly because I played football in college and my dad was a football coach and I grew up

00:27:03.359 --> 00:27:09.040
watching way too much film, but the more closer you are to the subject level matter, the better

00:27:09.040 --> 00:27:13.359
you are at your job. It doesn't mean that you need it for all roles. You can be a great coder

00:27:13.359 --> 00:27:19.599
and sort of learn that skillset along the way. And I mean, football is in some sense a complicated

00:27:19.599 --> 00:27:25.760
sport, but in another, anybody can learn it if you try to learn it, right. So it's not like it's

00:27:25.760 --> 00:27:30.880
too far away from, from somebody to learn. My mother-in-law complains that it's too hard to

00:27:30.880 --> 00:27:36.160
learn, but I would say in general, like you can figure this stuff out. But a lot of the things

00:27:36.160 --> 00:27:44.160
that we do is we just answer their questions. And I think the sort of second part of communicating

00:27:44.160 --> 00:27:48.079
that result is sometimes we are answering the questions that we know they're going to ask before

00:27:48.079 --> 00:27:54.719
they've asked them. And I think, I think the best presentations we give are the ones where they're

00:27:54.719 --> 00:28:00.079
asking a question and then I just click next and it's on the next slide, right. Or they ask a

00:28:00.079 --> 00:28:04.880
question and I say, yep, it's in the appendix, click a couple of slides forward and say, here it

00:28:04.880 --> 00:28:09.520
is, because you have to anticipate the questions they're going to ask. You have to, sometimes we're

00:28:09.520 --> 00:28:14.880
collecting data before they've asked us to collect data because we can tell, like we hear something

00:28:14.880 --> 00:28:21.040
in the media or we hear something that they're asking in the replay room or their coaches are

00:28:21.040 --> 00:28:25.680
asking. And we're like, all right, we're going to go build this because they didn't tell us to go

00:28:25.680 --> 00:28:30.880
collect data on quarterback slides. But we now know that quarterbacks are sliding more than ever

00:28:30.880 --> 00:28:35.680
before. We know quarterbacks are the most important position in football. So last year, Andrew Patton

00:28:35.680 --> 00:28:40.560
basically led a NFL data collection process in quarterback slides because we knew that when we

00:28:40.560 --> 00:28:45.520
got to the offseason, somebody was going to say, hey, how are our quarterbacks sliding? And it's

00:28:45.520 --> 00:28:49.599
like, actually we have that because we went out and collected it. So I would say that it's a

00:28:49.599 --> 00:28:55.199
combination of great data viz and then also being purposeful and sort of forward thinking with

00:28:55.199 --> 00:29:00.959
the questions that people are going to be wanting to ask. That's great. Thank you so much, Mike.

00:29:02.880 --> 00:29:05.920
Sanjay, I see you had your hand raised a little bit ago. Do you want to jump in here?

00:29:06.800 --> 00:29:15.439
Yeah, hi. I was curious when you said RFID tags are used to track players. And so what

00:29:15.439 --> 00:29:21.199
all data do you collect apart from just tracking the player, the speed, direction,

00:29:21.199 --> 00:29:27.119
what all is captured? Just was curious to know. Yeah, so it captures the XY coordinate data,

00:29:27.119 --> 00:29:33.359
two-dimensional. We don't get their height. The tags are like the size of your thumbnail,

00:29:33.359 --> 00:29:37.439
and they fit into the player's shoulder pads. And some players don't even know that they're

00:29:37.439 --> 00:29:42.000
wearing them. They turn on whenever they go on the field. You could watch players on the

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:49.040
sideline if you wanted to. I wouldn't recommend it. But then the league takes that data,

00:29:49.040 --> 00:29:53.439
they share. From the XY data, we get their speed acceleration. Because it's two chips,

00:29:53.439 --> 00:30:00.079
we also get their orientation. That's all curated and sent out to the teams from the league office.

00:30:01.520 --> 00:30:09.119
So you could watch NFL, and you'd see like fastest players or fastest acceleration speed.

00:30:10.079 --> 00:30:14.719
You could get change of direction from it without too much effort. So that's the type of thing that

00:30:14.719 --> 00:30:19.520
you would get from this data. And do you have an RFID on the ball also? Yes. Yeah, good question.

00:30:19.520 --> 00:30:25.760
Yeah, there's an RFID on the ball. With players, I would say it's accurate usually to within a

00:30:25.760 --> 00:30:31.359
couple inches. The ball has a larger margin of error, maybe closer to five or six inches.

00:30:32.319 --> 00:30:40.000
And then with all of it, with both the 22 players, the ball, there's also RFID tags in

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:43.920
things on the sideline, like the pylons and the chains. I don't think there's much use

00:30:44.560 --> 00:30:53.280
in those, but the league has been collecting it. And then it's all at frames of 10 frames per

00:30:53.280 --> 00:31:01.920
second, right? So a given player, a play is seven seconds long, you're going to get 70 observations

00:31:01.920 --> 00:31:05.760
of that player on that play. And you could animate it to sort of follow them around.

00:31:05.760 --> 00:31:09.119
You also get their data before the snap and after the snap. It's just a matter of what you find

00:31:09.119 --> 00:31:13.760
most useful. Aaron, I think you had a question related to that about the ball too. Do you want

00:31:13.760 --> 00:31:21.040
to jump in here? I think the question was kind of about like officiating. And let's see. Aaron said,

00:31:21.040 --> 00:31:25.920
I've always wondered why can't a tracker be placed on the ball to determine when it crosses the plane

00:31:25.920 --> 00:31:31.920
for a first down or touchdown. So is that something that's being looked at? Yeah, and I think

00:31:31.920 --> 00:31:36.880
Geraldine's question is similar. It is being looked at. There are a couple of differences

00:31:36.880 --> 00:31:45.040
that I think matter a lot. One is NFL stadiums are enormous and there's a lot of player overlap

00:31:45.040 --> 00:31:49.040
on almost every play. And so the cameras have to be further away, unlike tennis where they're right

00:31:49.040 --> 00:31:54.640
on the field. And unlike maybe a VAR decision in soccer where there's two, three players, maybe

00:31:54.640 --> 00:31:59.680
right in a tight space, arguably they're a lot more. So the technology that you can see in other

00:31:59.680 --> 00:32:08.079
sports is a little bit more complex to apply to football. In my now six years, there have been

00:32:08.079 --> 00:32:16.239
several attempts, some gaining more traction than others to do video-based spotting. It is a

00:32:16.239 --> 00:32:23.359
challenge. And the current accuracy margin of error of the football itself using the chip in the

00:32:23.359 --> 00:32:29.839
middle of the ball can't replace the sort of on-field spotting for a couple of reasons. One,

00:32:30.400 --> 00:32:38.000
I mentioned the margin of error. If you're saying the ball is here, but then you look on the film

00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:43.119
and it's actually here, it's really difficult to justify that to a viewer at home while you're

00:32:43.119 --> 00:32:49.439
making a first down decision or a decision on the goal line. And I think the second part there too

00:32:49.520 --> 00:32:55.199
is the ball spotting process at the NFL is based on the tip of the football without

00:32:56.640 --> 00:33:00.800
totally changing the construct of the chip in the football. We don't know that. And the chip

00:33:00.800 --> 00:33:05.439
is in the middle of football. It's been tried to put multiple chips in, then you're sort of

00:33:05.439 --> 00:33:10.239
messing around with the mechanics of how that feels at the quarterback. And we don't want to

00:33:10.239 --> 00:33:15.520
do that. So, you know, there are video-based attempts that my intuition is within a couple

00:33:15.520 --> 00:33:22.479
of years, there will be use cases of it that you'll see on air where the sort of technology

00:33:22.479 --> 00:33:29.680
is helping the process of spotting the football. But it's not as easy as sort of maybe it appears

00:33:29.680 --> 00:33:36.800
in the other sports. And I also think the other aspect for us is that pace of play is really

00:33:36.800 --> 00:33:42.800
important in the sense that tennis can have a break or soccer can have a break to look at this

00:33:42.800 --> 00:33:49.280
decision and maybe the ball isn't in play. The second the ball is put down, the ball's in play.

00:33:49.280 --> 00:33:57.040
There's no other than the couple stoppages for replay or in between downs, in between like a

00:33:57.040 --> 00:34:05.119
fourth down and a punt play or whatever. There's no example of sort of saying, pause, hold on,

00:34:05.119 --> 00:34:08.719
we're all going to wait, right? We just don't have that time. Coaches want the ball to move.

00:34:08.719 --> 00:34:14.800
We want the game to be three hours or so. And that sort of continued focus means, sure,

00:34:14.800 --> 00:34:18.639
you know, there might be a tool out there that's going to get us the exact right spot. But if it

00:34:18.639 --> 00:34:24.639
takes three minutes, you know, that's not a trade-off I think the league would be making.

00:34:24.639 --> 00:34:29.919
Thank you. I see Jared had a question and you put the star next to it, so I'll read it. But Jared

00:34:29.919 --> 00:34:36.399
asked, how does someone get into the NFL space as a data scientist to help improve player safety

00:34:36.399 --> 00:34:43.679
and performance? So I think there's a couple of ways. One is, I mean, there are, I mentioned IQV

00:34:43.679 --> 00:34:47.919
and BioCorps, but they are two companies we work with a lot and they're specifically targeting,

00:34:49.439 --> 00:34:52.879
you know, things like the epidemiology of injuries, return to play,

00:34:53.840 --> 00:35:00.239
injury trends based on how teams are playing, the equipment, you know, safest helmets,

00:35:00.320 --> 00:35:07.600
safest cleats, safest shoulder pads, or the sort of characteristics within a play that,

00:35:07.600 --> 00:35:14.879
you know, the orientation of player limbs that could lead to injury. So I think there are sort

00:35:14.879 --> 00:35:21.919
of things that are specific to the injury side of things that are part of it. Then there's also the

00:35:21.919 --> 00:35:27.439
maybe more performance side, which is all the teams want those same questions answered. And

00:35:27.439 --> 00:35:31.919
they have, you know, just like you see the next gen stats, clear tracking data in games,

00:35:33.199 --> 00:35:37.360
they get catapult data in practice, or there are other companies besides Catapult that do it,

00:35:37.360 --> 00:35:42.560
does it, but Catapult is probably the biggest one. So you have the same data that you get on

00:35:42.560 --> 00:35:46.399
your own players in practice. Now that's not data that the league office would get,

00:35:46.399 --> 00:35:52.159
but if you're on a team and you could sort of identify like, listen, this player has had two

00:35:52.159 --> 00:35:57.679
or three really hard days in a row, maybe that comes with an increased injury risk of a hamstring

00:35:57.679 --> 00:36:02.879
strain or something. I'm just, I'm not necessarily making that up, but that's hypothetical, right?

00:36:02.879 --> 00:36:08.080
So those would be the things that you would get into is thinking along, like, what happens within

00:36:08.080 --> 00:36:13.199
a practice and how to make sure that that player that put forth a certain load, that traveled a

00:36:13.199 --> 00:36:20.560
certain distance, that ran at his high speed for, you know, 10 minutes, which is maybe a lot,

00:36:20.719 --> 00:36:24.080
or three minutes, which maybe isn't a lot, like how are they going to perform the next day?

00:36:24.800 --> 00:36:28.719
Because ultimately the job of teams is to win games and you win games when your players are

00:36:28.719 --> 00:36:33.760
healthy. So the coaches understand the value of this too. So it's sort of a league level basis,

00:36:33.760 --> 00:36:37.199
but then also on a more micro level, the teams are also looking into it.

00:36:37.840 --> 00:36:42.639
Thank you. Nick, I see your hand was raised just a few seconds ago. Do you want to jump in here?

00:36:43.199 --> 00:36:47.520
Yeah, sorry. Sure. Coming off of here. Hi, everybody. Nice to talk to you.

00:36:48.080 --> 00:36:54.879
So my question kind of revolved around, I guess, communication of what you're finding and just kind

00:36:54.879 --> 00:37:01.360
of having some, like, a personal feel and read on, you know, football personnel and staff. So,

00:37:01.360 --> 00:37:05.439
you know, I know a lot, like the old guard guys might be, and folks in general, might be a little

00:37:05.439 --> 00:37:10.320
bit resistant to analytics and just kind of the philosophy. So I was wondering, and I know you

00:37:10.320 --> 00:37:15.439
kind of mentioned, like, you're doing more PowerPoint presentations and talking to people,

00:37:15.439 --> 00:37:21.840
like, how are you getting people to kind of buy into analytics as a whole? How can you take your,

00:37:21.840 --> 00:37:26.239
you know, the modeling that's the math and turn it into actual advice, but also in a,

00:37:26.239 --> 00:37:30.800
from a perspective that, like, is digestible for football coaches that are personnel,

00:37:30.800 --> 00:37:35.840
whoever might be working with you in a way that they can, you know, use it, accept it,

00:37:35.840 --> 00:37:39.199
and, you know, feel better about it. Because kind of around the football space, it seems like the

00:37:39.199 --> 00:37:43.120
word analytics is a little bit like a stink on it, if you know what I mean.

00:37:43.120 --> 00:37:48.399
Yeah, I haven't had a lot of pushback. Like, there hasn't, I mean, I've been here six years,

00:37:48.399 --> 00:37:51.439
there's not been a single meeting where somebody was like, I don't want to see your results,

00:37:51.439 --> 00:37:55.840
or I don't care about X, Y, or Z. I mean, I mentioned earlier that there are certainly

00:37:55.840 --> 00:38:00.560
times where I've thought the league maybe could have done this, or a certain team could have said,

00:38:00.560 --> 00:38:03.520
hey, we think we should prioritize this more, and maybe that hasn't happened.

00:38:04.560 --> 00:38:08.320
I think a lot of it comes back to, we're not trying to answer different questions that they

00:38:08.320 --> 00:38:11.280
are. We're trying to answer the same question they are, and we're just trying to put numbers to it.

00:38:11.760 --> 00:38:18.560
And, you know, there are lots of examples where we just get a sense of the questions that they're

00:38:18.560 --> 00:38:24.159
after, what they're interested in, and we say, here's what we're thinking. And I also think we're,

00:38:24.959 --> 00:38:28.080
you know, I think we do an appropriate job of pushing where we need to push,

00:38:28.080 --> 00:38:33.199
and then also saying sometimes, like, listen, I mean, there are a couple examples of random

00:38:33.199 --> 00:38:38.560
projections we've been working on in the last week where sometimes we've just said, honestly,

00:38:38.639 --> 00:38:44.320
like, we're giving you a projection for something for some time, but I wouldn't even really trust

00:38:44.320 --> 00:38:48.959
it. Like, I personally don't trust our own model, right, because there's too many uncertainties that,

00:38:49.600 --> 00:38:54.479
too much noise in the system. So I think we're also, we try to balance, like, when we push.

00:38:54.479 --> 00:39:01.199
And one of the advices I got from somebody, I think in hockey a couple years ago, is I was

00:39:01.199 --> 00:39:06.560
asking that person why their team didn't do something. And it was like, okay, you know,

00:39:06.639 --> 00:39:11.199
in hockey it was a specific thing that I thought teams could do to gain an edge. And their point

00:39:11.199 --> 00:39:17.280
was, this analyst that I talked to, is that they look at their role as they have a certain amount

00:39:17.280 --> 00:39:22.639
of times that they could really push. And sometimes you do it, and sometimes you say,

00:39:22.639 --> 00:39:27.120
like, listen, I think my team probably could increase my chances of winning by this,

00:39:27.120 --> 00:39:32.320
but there's something else that comes with it that maybe I don't want to, it's not necessarily,

00:39:32.320 --> 00:39:36.800
it moves the needle only this much, and it's not worth it. So I do think our team also tries

00:39:36.800 --> 00:39:42.639
to be a little bit purposeful with how we balance when we are saying, like, hey, this is something

00:39:42.639 --> 00:39:47.120
we should change, or this is something we should do, because, you know, we only get so many cracks

00:39:47.120 --> 00:39:52.479
at it. And, you know, there are times where I think, hey, we can really improve our decision

00:39:52.479 --> 00:39:56.479
making here. And there are other times where I would say, like, hey, listen, I can give you a

00:39:56.479 --> 00:40:01.360
number, but, you know, go with your gut, it's probably not going to be that far off. So I

00:40:01.360 --> 00:40:05.919
think our team is pretty smart about sort of adding all the caveats in the stars to sort of

00:40:05.919 --> 00:40:11.360
say, like, hey, the asterisk, right? Like, hey, take our results with a grain of salt. Like,

00:40:11.360 --> 00:40:15.760
so many things are happening in football, teams are changing, the rules are changing that,

00:40:15.760 --> 00:40:20.239
you know, assuming that maybe this is going to hold or that this is the best way to do it is

00:40:20.239 --> 00:40:24.320
not right. But then other times we try to really push for things. So it's kind of a balance of

00:40:24.320 --> 00:40:30.879
that. It's really helpful feedback. Listening to, like, all the different pieces of, like,

00:40:30.879 --> 00:40:35.520
data you're working with, or problems you're looking at solving, even some things that

00:40:35.520 --> 00:40:40.320
people haven't asked for yet. How do you prioritize what your team's working on?

00:40:41.840 --> 00:40:49.840
I don't have a great answer there. You know, like, a lot of it is, honestly, like, we'll,

00:40:51.120 --> 00:40:56.560
we have a meeting in a week or so with some executives. And my last slide is here are six

00:40:56.560 --> 00:41:02.479
things we can do this fall. Tell me where you would prefer we spend our time. So that maybe

00:41:02.479 --> 00:41:08.080
that's kind of part of is just getting a read on it. You know, we're not a, we're not totally

00:41:08.080 --> 00:41:12.080
obtuse to what we hear in the media in terms of what people are talking about. Because if clubs,

00:41:13.040 --> 00:41:17.760
you know, it's a weird, it's weird to be in a public facing industry. But if clubs leak it to

00:41:18.800 --> 00:41:23.840
some media organization, it's a nonzero chance it makes it makes it way back to our group.

00:41:24.639 --> 00:41:29.439
You know, like last, you're familiar with football, one of the things that that last year

00:41:29.439 --> 00:41:33.520
started early in the season is his teams would do what's called a push quarterback sneak where

00:41:33.520 --> 00:41:37.439
you would have quarterback lineup. And traditionally, they would sneak forward.

00:41:37.439 --> 00:41:42.000
Now you put somebody behind him and like two or three people are pushing. So some of the quarterback

00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:46.399
slide process, we were like, let's collect this data, because we saw it on pro football talk in

00:41:46.399 --> 00:41:50.560
week two or three. And it's like, if we don't collect it, they're going to get to the end of

00:41:50.560 --> 00:41:54.080
the year and complain about it. And it's going to be like, Oh, crap, we should have measured this.

00:41:54.080 --> 00:41:58.560
So it's like, okay, now we got to measure it. So it's just kind of being in tune with what's out

00:41:58.560 --> 00:42:03.520
there. The what we're seeing on the field, I mentioned, I know, Rachel, you asked what I

00:42:03.520 --> 00:42:09.120
like to do for fun. You know, I watch football for fun. But I also watch it knowing that whenever

00:42:09.120 --> 00:42:13.439
something happens, like sometimes there's going to be a question we need to answer Monday morning,

00:42:13.439 --> 00:42:19.040
how often does this happen? Is this getting worse? And addressing that, you know, we deal with a good

00:42:19.040 --> 00:42:23.679
number of questions from the clubs and from teams, sometimes from an education perspective,

00:42:23.679 --> 00:42:29.360
but then also sometimes from a, you know, complaint perspective, or they think they're being

00:42:31.600 --> 00:42:37.360
there's a perceived slight against them. So just trying to be a little bit aware of what's going

00:42:37.360 --> 00:42:43.919
on. And for us, honestly, that's just paying attention and watching. Thank you. Kayla,

00:42:43.919 --> 00:42:49.600
I see you had a question a bit earlier, as well about the types of tools they use. You want to

00:42:49.600 --> 00:42:55.120
jump in here? Sure. Yeah, I think I asked a question about if most of this work is done

00:42:55.120 --> 00:42:59.840
in Python and R, are there any particular packages? If so, or if that code is mostly internal,

00:42:59.840 --> 00:43:04.959
or if there's any other kind of like software typically used in NFL sports analytics?

00:43:04.959 --> 00:43:10.800
Yeah, a great good question. We, I would say we're more on the odd than the Python side,

00:43:10.800 --> 00:43:17.919
but there's, it's a kind of a decent mix. I've asked this to NFL team staffers. And one other,

00:43:17.919 --> 00:43:24.000
I think, good point that is just sort of exists is that teams are hiring more and more. So there's

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:29.600
more and more folks with our Python backgrounds going to teams. When I started, I want to say

00:43:29.600 --> 00:43:37.360
that there were maybe 70 or so data scientists, data scientists being a catch all term here,

00:43:38.320 --> 00:43:44.879
folks that were using football data to try and help the team on the field. Maybe 70 or so,

00:43:44.879 --> 00:43:49.760
and I think the most recent list is we're somewhere around 130 or 140. So within the last

00:43:49.760 --> 00:43:54.479
five years, teams have basically doubled their infrastructure on the football data side.

00:43:55.760 --> 00:44:00.800
And I, of that group, you know, being familiar with a lot of them, you know, our team probably

00:44:00.800 --> 00:44:07.600
knows the majority of those folks. I'd probably put it about 70, 30 R versus Python. And that's

00:44:07.600 --> 00:44:14.239
probably where our team sits, you know, internally. That's not, you know, certainly there are,

00:44:15.360 --> 00:44:20.639
I think right now, most postings are like, you have to know R or Python. You know, a good number

00:44:20.639 --> 00:44:25.600
of managers are probably more comfortable in R because of the, you know, where football data

00:44:25.600 --> 00:44:30.959
has been, but that doesn't necessarily mean that it's any better. And then I also think

00:44:30.959 --> 00:44:35.439
there's a growing number of roles for people that know neither, but know what football data is.

00:44:36.159 --> 00:44:42.800
So, and like, this would be like your communicator type role. So folks that maybe are really up to

00:44:42.800 --> 00:44:47.600
date with current football metrics and maybe have coaching experience or playing experience,

00:44:48.159 --> 00:44:52.719
and they want to be the translator. They want to be the person that is going and saying, hey,

00:44:53.280 --> 00:44:58.560
you know, I can't fit that neural net model, but I know you can, and I know what it's going to give

00:44:58.560 --> 00:45:03.520
me as a result. And this is, I think what's going to help this coach or this assistant GM or whatever.

00:45:04.320 --> 00:45:10.080
So I would even say there's even a good amount of room in football analytics for non-coders,

00:45:10.080 --> 00:45:16.239
right? People who, you know, have some ability to know what's going on in the background,

00:45:17.040 --> 00:45:21.280
know a little bit about modeling and know what the strengths and weaknesses are,

00:45:21.280 --> 00:45:28.479
while maybe not being able to do it on player tracking data. But also having that ability,

00:45:28.479 --> 00:45:31.840
you know, you really have to know football, right? To sort of get into that role. And not

00:45:31.840 --> 00:45:37.520
every team has them, but you know, if you stay up to date on the big data bull and on next-gen stats

00:45:37.520 --> 00:45:42.239
and on sort of public facing research, you can provide a lot of value to your team, right? In

00:45:42.239 --> 00:45:46.239
terms of identifying trends that are meaningful and maybe trends that you would want to ignore.

00:45:46.239 --> 00:45:49.679
That's really cool. What would that role be, the translator?

00:45:50.959 --> 00:45:55.360
I mean, if so, for example, you're an offensive coordinator for a team and you want to build a

00:45:55.360 --> 00:46:00.320
scouting report, you want to build a dashboard that says, here's what the opposing defense is

00:46:00.320 --> 00:46:06.560
going to do each week. There are lots of data scientists that could do that. A good number of

00:46:06.560 --> 00:46:11.280
them, especially the ones that have spent the last four or five years in football tracking data,

00:46:11.280 --> 00:46:16.719
might not know the names that your team is using for what that opposing defense is running,

00:46:16.719 --> 00:46:20.639
right? They might be able to separate man from zone coverage, but they might not be able to

00:46:20.639 --> 00:46:25.919
separate cover two from cover four from cover six, or they might not be able to understand the strong

00:46:25.919 --> 00:46:30.719
sideline backer for the weak sideline backer. And so now you need somebody to sort of say like,

00:46:30.719 --> 00:46:35.520
okay, this is what the coach is looking for. This is what this term is. This is what this splits is.

00:46:35.520 --> 00:46:40.479
And then your job is to code it all, right? And to sort of work with that communicator to make,

00:46:40.479 --> 00:46:46.800
to help that. I guess I was just curious, like what that title is, like how do people find

00:46:46.800 --> 00:46:51.760
those kinds of roles? I would, a lot of them would just be like analysts or even like

00:46:51.760 --> 00:46:58.000
quality control coach. Like Seth Wilder from ESPN on Twitter has a really good link.

00:46:58.000 --> 00:47:03.040
I'm sure somebody can find and put in the chat. Football, all sports analytics careers are like

00:47:03.040 --> 00:47:08.239
this. There's a bunch of different names for people that are doing the same stuff. And it's

00:47:08.239 --> 00:47:14.719
kind of weird. Like my title is director of senior director of football data analytics, right?

00:47:15.760 --> 00:47:20.080
I could be senior director of football analytics research or senior data, probably not a senior

00:47:20.080 --> 00:47:24.320
data scientist anymore because I don't code as much, but some are analysts, some are data

00:47:24.320 --> 00:47:33.040
scientists, some are whatever. And there's not exactly one perfect name for it. But yeah,

00:47:33.040 --> 00:47:39.760
it's probably an analyst type of role. But it is a lot of times like football coaches

00:47:39.760 --> 00:47:44.800
know a lot and they're using data, even if they're not telling you they're using data,

00:47:44.800 --> 00:47:48.800
right? They're going to tell you that they're going to target the left cornerback on the other

00:47:48.800 --> 00:47:52.879
team because they turned their hips too early. Well, you could probably use an analyst to go

00:47:52.879 --> 00:47:56.719
figure out when they turn their hips too early, what does that mean, right? And so a lot of times

00:47:56.719 --> 00:48:03.600
you're just trying to communicate to be that line because unfortunately or fortunately,

00:48:04.639 --> 00:48:10.479
that offense coordinator might not have all the time in the world for this person to advise

00:48:10.479 --> 00:48:15.600
them on it. So that's kind of where you need some of the translators. Well, thank you. George,

00:48:15.600 --> 00:48:20.879
I see you had a question in the chat a few minutes ago. Do you want to jump in? Oh, yeah. Thanks. So

00:48:20.879 --> 00:48:25.120
yeah, I was just wondering, this is something I always think about whenever I'm watching a sporting

00:48:25.120 --> 00:48:35.840
event, is how do I get my organization to report at the level of what I see, like the NFL or ESPN

00:48:35.840 --> 00:48:41.679
or any in-game commentator reporting on? The kind of analytics that come out of their mouths, I'm

00:48:41.679 --> 00:48:48.000
just in awe of. And it's historical. Sometimes it's like, well, the last quarterback who did

00:48:48.000 --> 00:48:55.120
this was in 1978, and he had like blonde hair and went to this college. And I'm like, I mean,

00:48:55.120 --> 00:48:58.239
first of all, like, I don't even think that's relevant. But the fact that they could pull that

00:48:58.239 --> 00:49:05.439
out of nowhere in 10 seconds is pretty impressive. I've tried doing that in my field in HR in the

00:49:05.439 --> 00:49:13.840
past. And that's always sort of the bar that I have. But I'm just curious, how does one go about

00:49:13.840 --> 00:49:22.159
even trying to achieve that level of analytics? It's almost like a research team. And the NFL does

00:49:22.159 --> 00:49:28.320
have a research team that they, before every game, they provide the media with an enormous,

00:49:30.159 --> 00:49:36.479
you know, basically like a folder, right, of all the things. And this is automatically generated

00:49:36.479 --> 00:49:43.520
using various tools, right, of all the things that are applicable to these teams. And it's

00:49:43.520 --> 00:49:48.080
almost like scouting reports that you would see of like a baseball player or a football player.

00:49:48.639 --> 00:49:52.560
And so when a wide receiver catches the ball, the commentator is able to go and say, oh,

00:49:52.560 --> 00:49:58.320
this is interesting. He was, you know, caught the highest, you know, red zone target rate of any

00:49:58.320 --> 00:50:02.959
tight end last year, right. And a lot of it's not because they've done it. It's because somebody's,

00:50:02.959 --> 00:50:07.760
you know, sort of handed that to them. We don't do a lot with it. That's maybe certainly more on

00:50:07.760 --> 00:50:14.399
the media side. But I do know that that's, you know, the research and media team's job is to

00:50:14.399 --> 00:50:20.000
prep basically a portfolio for them to pull from. And I do think one of the things that they're

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:25.360
balancing is how do I take a lot of the new metrics that nobody's ever heard of versus some

00:50:25.360 --> 00:50:29.600
of the old things like, you know, everybody knows the blonde hair, right, like that they could,

00:50:29.600 --> 00:50:34.800
you could pull from that that maybe wouldn't make as much sense. So that's kind of where I

00:50:34.800 --> 00:50:40.080
think football data is now is how much is too much and what is a reasonable thing to give our

00:50:40.080 --> 00:50:44.959
audience. Maybe an area we don't deal as much with, but it is relevant to some of the research

00:50:44.959 --> 00:50:50.000
they get. I realize I missed a question over on Slido. So I want to make sure I get to some of

00:50:50.000 --> 00:50:55.520
the, one of the anonymous ones, but it was, you're going to have to help me with this acronym. Does

00:50:56.159 --> 00:51:02.399
GAIT, G-A-I-T, analysis of the players have any impact on their performance? And what are the

00:51:02.399 --> 00:51:09.520
KPIs that you generally look for for a player's potential impact? So we've tended to stay away

00:51:09.520 --> 00:51:17.199
from some of the performance metrics. And I think that's what GAIT would be. And so I wouldn't be

00:51:17.199 --> 00:51:23.679
able to know as much there. I think the weird angle we would come at performance would be like,

00:51:23.679 --> 00:51:31.120
how does the league set policies or rules for a schedule or for practices that allow players to

00:51:31.120 --> 00:51:36.959
reach a level of performance? So we've done a lot of research on, for example, what is the impact

00:51:36.959 --> 00:51:42.320
of playing a team that just had a bye week the previous week? Each team gets one bye week a

00:51:42.320 --> 00:51:48.320
season. If you're the Jets and you're playing the Giants and the Giants have had two weeks of

00:51:48.320 --> 00:51:55.040
practice, maybe is that, what type of advantage does that provide you on the field? So it's a

00:51:55.040 --> 00:52:00.399
different performance angle. You know, like another ones would be like back to back to back road games

00:52:00.399 --> 00:52:08.000
or travel events. There's a different type of performance thing, but I think that's probably

00:52:08.000 --> 00:52:13.520
the closest to the thing that the league could control. Ultimately, for a lot of legal reasons,

00:52:13.520 --> 00:52:18.000
we're not as in tune with some of the performance stuff on the team side, at least the league

00:52:18.000 --> 00:52:24.479
office. But I do know the teams are obviously interested in it. Well, thank you. Brittany,

00:52:24.479 --> 00:52:30.639
I don't think we got to your question yet. Do you want to jump in here? I think you had a,

00:52:31.280 --> 00:52:39.280
oh, you unmuted. I'll have you ask it. Yeah. So I know that with the introduction of the RFID tags,

00:52:39.280 --> 00:52:45.439
I'm sure that there's a bunch of new data points that you're exploring that previously haven't

00:52:45.439 --> 00:52:51.280
been explored. But also I'm sure that there may be changes to like rules of thumb or heuristics

00:52:51.840 --> 00:52:55.840
around already existing data points that maybe are coming into play now that you have a little

00:52:55.840 --> 00:53:02.000
bit more specific data. Can you talk through how you've been kind of evangelizing those new and or

00:53:02.639 --> 00:53:06.159
maybe different than expected things and how you've been getting buy-in from your business

00:53:06.159 --> 00:53:14.000
partners around that? Good question. We've, and I can share a little bit of this, but we,

00:53:14.000 --> 00:53:19.360
because they shared it this past off season. But one area was sort of stuff I was just mentioning

00:53:19.360 --> 00:53:24.959
is that we did a lot of research on what I would call scheduling inequities and basically how

00:53:25.760 --> 00:53:31.040
things that the league sets impact game outcomes. And there were a good number of surprising ones

00:53:31.040 --> 00:53:35.439
where things that I think most people would perceive as having a big impact on a team's

00:53:35.439 --> 00:53:42.159
chance of winning the game maybe didn't matter as much. And so, you know, the scheduling team

00:53:42.159 --> 00:53:46.719
mentioned that when they made their schedule this year, they took some of our advice to heart.

00:53:47.280 --> 00:53:53.840
And a lot of that honestly was just trust, right? I think we had to do a really thorough job of

00:53:53.840 --> 00:53:57.600
looking at all possible metrics that they thought they might want. So they didn't say,

00:53:57.600 --> 00:54:03.040
go look at X, Y, and Z. It's, we sort of thought from our football background, what are the possible

00:54:03.040 --> 00:54:09.679
ways that anybody out there could ever, you know, see an on-field impact of these things? And,

00:54:10.320 --> 00:54:15.919
you know, when we presented, it was thorough. It had every possible angle. And I think because of

00:54:16.959 --> 00:54:22.080
that approach where it's sort of saying like, hey, we're not going to give you one thing and say,

00:54:22.080 --> 00:54:26.000
all right, we're done. We solved it. It's going to be, we're going to give you a bunch of different

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:31.439
ways of looking at it. A couple of different outcomes, a couple of different time points.

00:54:32.159 --> 00:54:36.159
We're also going to be, acknowledge our limitations and things we don't know.

00:54:36.879 --> 00:54:42.560
So for example, you know, it might not be the case that teams that are playing three road games in

00:54:42.560 --> 00:54:48.399
a row in the NFL lose more often, but it is the case that if you're on a team and you play three

00:54:48.399 --> 00:54:52.959
road games, you're away from your family for three weeks. And that doesn't just mean that we can go

00:54:52.959 --> 00:54:56.800
throw teams on the road for, you know, three, four, five, six weeks in a row, because that's

00:54:56.800 --> 00:55:01.840
going to have other impacts that maybe we're not measuring. So it's not a great answer, Brittany,

00:55:01.840 --> 00:55:07.679
but it's honestly, it's just trust, right? It's building up a repertoire of trying to look at a

00:55:07.679 --> 00:55:15.120
bunch of different things in a bunch of different ways. There isn't, it's very rare. I hope for my,

